PSEUDOCODE
==========

Define blink intervals array: [100ms, 250ms, 500ms, 1000ms, 2000ms]
Set current interval index to 0

Initialize SysTick -> 1ms timebase
Initialize PA5 as output (LED)
Initialize PC13 as input with pull-up (Button)

Track last_toggle time and last_blink state via ms_ticks

Loop forever:

    // Non-blocking LED toggle
    If (ms_ticks - last_toggle) >= intervals[index]:
        Toggle LED
        Update last_toggle = ms_ticks

    // Non-blocking button polling with debounce
    If PC13 is LOW and button was previously released:
        Wait 10ms (debounce via ms_ticks)
        If PC13 still LOW:
            Advance index -> (index + 1) % 5
            Mark button as pressed
	    Wait for releasing the button

    If PC13 is HIGH:
        Mark button as released

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

PIN MAP
=======

PA5   =>  Onboard LED (LD4)   - Active HIGH
PC13  =>  Onboard User Button - Active LOW

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COMMON MISTAKES AND DEBUG TIPS
==============================

* Reading ms_ticks multiple times in one loop iteration, ms_ticks is volatile
  and can change between reads since SysTick ISR fires every 1ms. If we read it
  twice in the same logic block we may get two different values and get subtle
  timing bugs. Snapshot it once at the top of the loop with
  uint32_t now = ms_ticks and use now throughout.

* Blocking while for release inside a non-blocking loop, This program is mostly
  non-blocking, but keeps a short blocking wait for button release. This is a
  pragmatic trade-off since button release is sub-second. After some program
  onwards with EXTI, both press and release are fully interrupt-driven and the
  main loop stays completely free.

* Interval index out of bounds, Using % NUM_INTERVALS on the index ensures it
  wraps from 4 back to 0 cleanly. If we hardcode % 5 and later change the array,
  we introduce a mismatch. Tie it to the constant.

* led_state tracking vs reading ODR, Rather than reading back ODR to know the
  current LED state (which is a read-modify-write), we track state in a separate
  variable. Cleaner and avoids the same atomicity concern as (ODR ^= ).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

EXTRA NOTES
===========

* This is the core pattern for all future main loops. The if ((now - last_event)
  >= interval) pattern is the foundation of cooperative bare-metal
  scheduling. Every future program that needs to do multiple things
  simultaneously: blink, read ADC, send UART, will stack these non-blocking `if
  blocks` on top of each other in the same while(1). Understand this pattern
  deeply here.

* Why not use TIM2 here, TIM2 was freed intentionally. From next Program onwards
  TIM2 is repurposed for PWM output, where it must run continuously in the
  background. SysTick takes over all coarse millisecond timing from here
  on. Each peripheral has a role and we try not to double-up.

* Extending this pattern, we could add a second array for LED-on duty
  (asymmetric blink - short flash vs long on) and a second index for it. Or add
  a timeout that returns to default speed if no button press for 5
  seconds. These are small additions on top of the same non-blocking skeleton.

